review_blob: Pours a thick, dark black with an off-brown head. The aroma is of slightly sweet toasty malts and coffee. The taste is of burnt toast, coffee and hop bitterness. It has a smooth but rich mouthfeel, and it coats my tongue nicely. Its a little too burnt/bitter for my personal taste, but its a great stout beer.

Yellow appearance. The smell is of some sort of citrus soda. The taste is horrible. It has a chemical, artificial nasty taste, like someone mixed citrus soda with beer. Did I mention that it tastes horrible? Drainpour to the max!

Pours a clear golden yellow with a thin white head. It has some decent lacing, and is quite carbonated to the end. The aroma is of very sweet rock candy with not much else present in the nose. The taste is of very dry, tart hops with a hint of toasted bread. Not as sweet as I was expecting based on the aroma, and perhaps a little too dry and tart for my liking, especially since it really lacks character other than the tartness (kind of like drinking carbonated water when the soda machine is messed up).

Pours a deep amber, verging on being brown, with a fairly thick, off-white head. The aroma is of caramel malts, burnt toast and ripe bananas. The taste is of very sweet caramel malt with some burnt notes too. To me, the malt is too dark and it has too much of a caramel sweetness. I would have preferred a slightly lighter Vienna-style lager.

Pours a slightly off-white hazy milky yellow sort of color. It smells like Fresca! It tastes like Fresca too! I love it, although I wouldnt really say its "beer" in any meaningful sense of the word. Very cleansing and refreshing.

Pours a clear yellow with little head or lacing. The aroma is mostly generic cluster hops. The taste is like hop-water. It says on the bottle that its gluten free, although I think this sticker might have been put on it by the store I bought it from since its not in any pictures Ive found on the internet. Given this, Im guessing its made mostly with rice, and it tastes like such. Its drinkable, but not anything noteworthy.

Pours a clear light straw yellow with a thin head, minimal lacing. The aroma is of sweet, lightly toasted malt, a touch of hops and skunk. Taste is predominately skunk, but you can taste the malt which has a nice burnt toast character but is light at the same time (sort of like very light rye bread). Not a bad beer, but I hate that it was skunked because its probably pretty decent on tap.

Pours a fairly clear harvest-moon orange with little head or lacing. The aroma is of sweet rock candy and wet dog. The taste is of bitter hops, but without much discernible flavour per se. The mouthfeel is very watery, and it tastes a lot like mineral water with some quinine. Very disappointing. Its sad when I have to chase a beer with vodka in order to get the taste out of my mouth.
Pours a light yellow with no head or lacing. The aroma is of rich yeasty wheat rolls with little hops. The taste is of bitter pine sap and wheat. Yummy yummy!

Pours a light yellow with minimal head or lacing. The aroma is of sweet apples. It has a crisp, clean taste that is neither overly sweet nor particularly dry. I wish it leaned a little more to one way or the other, because as it stands it tastes like a fairly generic, middle of the road cider that appeals to everyone but pleases no one.
Pours a dark yellow with a thin white head. It has a sweet, toasty corn flake aroma with a hint of hops. The taste is of piney hops and a light, smooth, slightly sweet cereal finish. Not bad!

Smells like a sweet grape slush from Sonic. Yep! Thats what it tastes like too, a slightly melted, fizzy grape flush from Sonic. Would I consider this a replacement for beer? No. It is awesome in its own right? Yep!!!
Pours a clear yellow with a thin head. The taste is of thin, watery fizz with a hint of malt and hops, but mostly water. Its chuggable, but is it drinkable?

Pours a fizzy light green/yellowish colour. It has a slightly sweet, limey aroma. The taste is of lemon/lime soda with some chemical notes here and there. Hard to see how this is beer, but Im drunk and chowing down on a burrito al pastor and some frijoles, so its not too bad from where Im standing. Still, I wouldnt really compare it to beer, but more of a cooler type drink.

Pours a bright, fizzy pink. The taste is of some kind of strawberry mixer/wine cooler with some decent carbonation. It has a slight hint of alcohol/chemical, but its pretty tasty. Even being malt based, I have a hard time comparing this to beer, nor would I want to drink this if I was in a beer mood. But, since Im making Mexican food tonight, this is a pretty convenient margarita-esque drink.

Pours a clear yellow. The aroma is fairly nondeScript, typical pale lager. The taste is of a cheap, poorly made clone of Strohs. Meh... Poor attempt at a clone of a beer thats barely decent to begin with.

Mediocre cider. It tasted like typical store-bought apple juice with a little bit of added sugar and a hint of alcohol. It wasnt as dry as the majority of ciders Ive had, and didnt really taste like it was made with great apples. It was just sort of meh, appley enough without being appletastic.
beer_name: Mikes Hard Smashed Apple Cider Classic Dry

review_blob: Pours a clear yellow with a very thin head. It has an aroma of skunk that can be smelled a mile away. The taste is pretty much pure skunk with a hint of hop bitterness thrown in. I can also taste a slight sweetness, but mostly just skunk. Probably not a bad beer fresh on tap, but more or less worthless in a bottle.

Pours a clear yellow with a moderate white head. The aroma is of pure skunk. The taste is of skunk and bitter hops. It has a nice hop bite and the malt is decent. Too bad its pure skunk, otherwise it might be a decent lager with some decent hoppage.

Pours a clear, dark orange with a thick, off-white head. The aroma is of faint malt with a little hops. The taste is of sweet malt syrup with a hint of hop bitterness on the back of my tongue. Not a bad beer, and definitely chuggable.

Pours a dark black with very little head. It has a rich, burnt coffee aroma. The taste is of bitter malt, similar to burnt rice. It has a smooth, creamy texture. Perfect texture for a porter, and a very nice beer.

Pours a fairly clear leathery-amber. The aroma is of sweet malted barley that is just slightly roasted but not particularly carmelised. The taste is similar to the aroma, only with a nice bitter snap at the tip of my tongue. Good beer!

Pours a very clear, light, mead-like yellow/white. It has no real scent. The taste is of slightly sweet, slightly corny malt with no real hops. Not dry enough to be a good light beer IMO, tastes more like a generic macro lager. Also the ABV is frustratingly low.

Pours a clear yellow with a thin, white head. It has a fairly nondeScript aroma of malt and hops. The taste is similar, nondeScript. A little malt, a little hops, but not much of either. Tastes like a very well-made macro lager, but nothing really special other than that.
Pours a clear orange with a thin white head. It has a sweet, slightly piney (but very subtle) aroma. The taste is of bitter pine with some bitter malt near the end. Tasty!

Pours a clear amber with minimal head. It has a malty, bready aroma of barley and a hint of hops. The taste is of thin, watery barley water. Tastes similar to Goya Malta or something, very light for its colour. No discernable defects really, just very bland, watery and more or less meh...

Pours a clear ruby red with a thick, white head. It has an aroma of pine and dry-roasted, browned malt (although not too roasted/caramelised, just lightly). It tastes like alcohol and pine. I get a little bit of the dry malt taste at the end followed by bitterness, but the alcohol and pine at the beginning predominate. Not a horrible beer, and one I might drink again, but I cant say Id go out of my way to get it either.
Pours a clear amber with a thick, white head. It has a sweet, oaky aroma. The taste is of light amber malt with a hint of vanilla. The mouthfeel is very watery. Okay beer, but nothing special.

Pours a clear yellow with no head but slight lacing. It has a very sweet aroma and smells like braeburn apples (Im a greengrocer). The taste is of sweet apples and little more. Like apple juice with a kick! Its a little too sweet for my taste.
Pours a clear copper with a thick white head. The aroma is of wet malt and a hint of pine. The taste is of bitter, piney hops with a wet, metallic malty finish. Overall, pretty good! Opa!

Pours a deep golden yellow with no head. It has a sweet aroma of apples mixed with ginger. The taste is, similarly, buttery apples with ginger in the mix. The ginger is ever-present, and borders on being too strong without crossing the line. Very good for a somewhat non-traditional cider, better than some plain ciders.

Pours a clear yellow with a medium, white head. It has a corny, sweet aroma. The taste is of cornmeal but rather than sweet it has a dry hop (Willamette?) aftertaste. In the end, its still a rather dull adjunct lager, but its better than any of the other Project 12 beers.
Pours a slightly dark yellow with no head at all. It has a sweet aroma. The taste is of dishwater and sugar. Drainpour...

Pours a clear yellow with a very thin, quickly dissipating, head. It has a very pronounced aroma of sweet creamed corn. The taste is of very sweet malt, mostly corn, with a slight touch of hops at the end before returning to corn. Not that good, way too sweet and corny - almost like an ice beer.

Pours a deep copper with a thick, white head. It has a sweet, slightly fruity malt aroma. The taste is of dry-roasted malt that is sweet and fruity at first but more tart as it goes down. It has a medium mouthfeel, perhaps more on the thin side but not overly. Great beer, although to me it tastes more like a doppelbock than a dubbel.

Pours a dark black with a moderate, tan head. It has an aroma of roasted malts. The taste is of semi-dry caramel malts with a little hop bitterness. It also has a slightly vegetal aftertaste, somewhat like roasted pumpkin in the winter. Not bad at all...

Pours dark black with a thick, white head. It has a sweet, malty aroma. The taste is of dry, burnt malt that is reminiscent of over-toasted bread. It has a thick mouthfeel, and the burnt-toast taste is predominant. No malt sweetness. Great black lager!

Pours a dark, opaque black with a thick, tan head. It has a roasted aroma similar to light coffee. The taste is of burnt (in a good way) malts with caramelised malt and a dominating metallic taste. It has a thin mouthfeel. This tastes like Guinness with just a thinner body, and it also has the same metallic taste I find in all Guinness products which is one reason Im not a huge fan of Guinness despite loving black beers. Its just lightweight Guinness, nothing particularly new or exciting.

Pours a clear, light copper with no head. It has a sweet, corn and oat malt aroma with little hops. The taste is of very light corn malt with little hop flavour or bitterness. It honestly tastes like light beer with food colouring more than a truly flavourful Vienna lager.

Pours a hazy, rusty orange with a very thin head. It has a fresh aroma of pine tar, sweet grapefruit and sugar. The taste is of dry, bitter grapefruit on the tip with the thick pine tar notes coming in on the back of my mouth and lingering for some time. It has a moderate mouthfeel, and goes down smooth but very dry. Great textbook IPA!

Pours a clear light yellow with little/no head. It has an aroma of fusel oils and sweet apples. The taste is of dry apples with a lot of fusel overtones. Id rate this higher, but its really fusely and chemically. Not the worst cider Ive had, but Ive had better.

Pours a light yellowish colour with a white, thin head. The aroma is like lemon-lime soda. The taste is more or less the same, watered down lemon-lime soda with some fusel notes and slight pale malt taste buried way under. It tastes more like lemon-lime soda thats been left in the car and all of the ice is melted than anything remotely similar to beer (even light beer). Meh. Meh. Meh...

Pours a hazy, light-orange colour that looks a lot like shanty with a frothy head. The aroma is of light orange and citrus hops with some earthy undertones. The taste is very dry and slightly fruity - again, somewhat orangey - with slightly sweet notes towards the back of my mouth. It also tastes fairly yeasty in a not particularly pleasant way. Not the worst beer Ive ever had, but it tastes strikingly similar to the orange-and-honey "wine" that Ive made a few times using bread yeast - a little too similar...

Pours a dark, ruby brown with a thick, off-white head and good lacing. The aroma is fairly standard, a little hops and a little roasted grain. The taste is of a slightly watered malt with hints of dry-roasted nuts and brown bread. A pretty average bock - no noticeable flaws but nothing exceptional.

Pours a clear, light straw with no real head at all, despite the fact that it has fairly high carbonation. The aroma is of slightly skunked oatmeal (despite the fact that it was in a brown bottle) with minimal hops. The taste, likewise, is of skunk and light, fairly bland, vegetal malt with a light hop finish (cluster hops? Something along those lines). Not horrible, but not worth the upcharge that this beer sells for.

Pours an opaque hue that is mostly black, but with reddish purple tinges under the light. It has a quickly dissipating, off-white head. The aroma is of dry roasted malt and a sort of Doppelbock pumpernickel smell. The taste is pretty similar, dry roasted malt with hints of pumpernickel and rye. The alcohol is fairly strong, IMO a little overwhelming, and it has a slightly cloying mouthfeel that I think is a little too syrupy for me.
beer_name: Samuel Adams Imperial Series Wee Heavy

review_blob: Pours a slightly hazy, light straw yellow with a thick, foamy white head. The aroma is of sweet malt, bread yeast and pears - almost cidery. The taste is dry and crisp with hints of cloves and bananas. The clove/banana taste is a little less subtle than I prefer, but its not quite as overwhelming as with other beers of similar styles. Not a bad beer, but a little odd IMO.

Pours a very light copper with a thin, quickly dissipating head. It has a very mild aroma of citrusy hops. The taste is slightly citrusy at first with piney, hoppy notes towards the end. I didnt really pick up on very much malt flavour, and the mouthfeel is a little thin for my liking.

Pours a deep ruby with a thick, white head. The aroma is of dry, syrupy malt - somewhat like molasses. The taste is of dry, rich molasses - but not sweet or cloying - with overtones of wheatberries or grape nut cereal. Tastes a lot more like a doppelbock than a brown ale, but overall a great brew.

Pours a clear off-white. It has a fresh aroma of apples and, well, apples! The taste is sweet and apple-ish and slightly crisp. Slightly sweeter than many ciders Im used to, although it lacks the solvent taste of many. A little on the watery side if I do say.
